[ctns_make id='axIdentRealS1']

    [ctns_front]
Field Axioms - Identity<br/><br/>Real Numbers $$\mathbb{R}$$
    [/ctns_front]
        
    [ctns_back style='font-size:80%;']
For the set of real numbers $$\mathbb{R}$$ and all $$x \in \mathbb{R},$$<br/><br/>
there is an element $$0 \in \mathbb{R}$$ such that<br/>
$$x + 0 = x,$$<br/><br/>
and there is an element $$1 \in \mathbb{R}$$ such that<br/>
$$x \cdot 1 = x.$$ 
    [/ctns_back]
    
[/ctns_make]


[ctns_make id='axInverseRealS1']

    [ctns_front]
Field Axioms - Inverse<br/><br/>Real Numbers $$\mathbb{R}$$
    [/ctns_front]
        
    [ctns_back style='font-size:80%;']
For the set of real numbers $$\mathbb{R}$$ and all $$x \in \mathbb{R},$$<br/><br/>
there is an element $$-x \in \mathbb{R}$$ such that<br/>
$$x + (-x) = 0,$$<br/><br/>
and there is an element $$\frac{1}{x} \in \mathbb{R}$$ such that
$$x \cdot \left( \frac{1}{x} \right) = 1.$$
    [/ctns_back]
    
[/ctns_make]


[ctns_make id='axFieldS1']

    [ctns_front]
Axiom
    [/ctns_front]
        
    [ctns_back style='font-size:80%;']
An <strong>axiom</strong> is a mathematical statement
that serves as the starting point from which all other statements
are logically derived. <br/><br/>An axiom can neither be derived by logic, nor demonstrated by mathematical proof.
    [/ctns_back]
    
[/ctns_make]


[ctns_make id='axFieldS2']

    [ctns_front]
A set is a field if ...
    [/ctns_front]
        
    [ctns_back style='width:60%;']
A set is a <strong>field</strong> if it satisfies all 12 field axioms.
    [/ctns_back]
    
[/ctns_make]


[ctns_make id='axFieldS3']

    [ctns_front]
A field is a set ...
    [/ctns_front]
        
    [ctns_backspeak]
A field is a set F with two binary operations addition and multiplication that obey the twelve field axioms for closure, associativity, commutativity, distributivity, identity, and inverse.
    [/ctns_backspeak]
        
    [ctns_back style='font-size:45%;']
<div>A <strong>field</strong> is a set $$\mathbb{F}$$ with two binary operations, addition ($$+$$) and multiplication ($$\cdot$$), that obey the 12 field axioms for $$x, y, z \in \mathbb{F},$$</div><br/>
<div>
<div>
<div><strong>name</strong></div>
<ul>
<li>closure</li>
<li>associativity</li>
<li>commutativity</li>
<li>distributivity</li>
<li>identity</li>
<li>inverses
</li></ul>
</div>
<div>
<div><strong>addition</strong></div>
<ul>
<li>$$x+y \in \mathbb{F}$$, &nbsp; $$x+y$$ is unique</li>
<li>$$(x+y)+z = x+(y+z)$$</li>
<li>$$x+y=y+x$$</li>
<li>$$x \cdot (y + z ) = x \cdot y + x \cdot z$$</li>
<li>$$x+0=x$$</li>
<li>$$x+(-x) = 0$$</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div>
<div><strong>multiplication</strong></div>
<ul>
<li>$$x \cdot y \in \mathbb{F}$$, &nbsp; $$x \cdot y$$ is unique</li>
<li>$$(x \cdot y) \cdot z = x \cdot (y \cdot z)$$</li>
<li>$$x \cdot y = y \cdot x$$</li>
<li>$$(x + y) \cdot z = x \cdot z + y \cdot z$$</li>
<li>$$x \cdot 1 = x$$</li>
<li>$$x \cdot \frac{1}{x} = 1, \; x \neq 0$$</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
    [/ctns_back]
    
[/ctns_make]

[/ctns_demo]
